    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A Study of Intercarrier Interference (ICI) Reduction Methods for Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing (OFDM) Based Multi Carrier Wireless System</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Kumar.R</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Intercarrier Interference<br />Orthogonal Frequency</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2008 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0010</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing (OFDM) is a special form
of multicarrier modulation where a single high speed data stream is
transmitted over a number of lower rate sub carriers. OFDM is a strong
candidate for commercial high speed broadband wireless communications. It
has a number of unique features. It is robust against multipath fading and inter
symbol interference. It allows for efficient use of the available RF spectrum
through the use of adaptive modulation and power allocation across the sub
carriers. It is also robust against narrow band interference. It does not require
continuous bandwidth for operation. Current trends suggest that OFDM will
be the modulation of choice for fourth generation broadband multimedia
wireless communication systems. However, there are several issues that need
to be overcome before OFDM finds widespread use in modern wireless
communication systems.
The OFDM system is very vulnerable to the phase noise or frequency
offset. The intercarrier interference (ICI) components results from the
frequency offset. This breaks the orthogonal characteristics between sub
carriers which leads to performance degradation considerably. There have
been many studies carried out in the past on frequency offset and ICI. The
countermeasures for ICI are frequency domain equalization, self-cancellation
and time domain windowing. For the above methods bit error rate (BER)
performance are studied.
vi
In this proposed thesis, the existing methods for reducing ICI in OFDM
system are analysed, particularly frequency offset correction by statistically
estimating and canceling the offset at the receiver by Maximum Likelihood
Estimation (MLE) algorithm is studied. An Extended Kalman Filtering (EKF)
method is proposed to improve BER performance over the previously studied
methods. The Kalman filter is used to predict and update phases for accurate
estimate than the self cancellation and MLE method.
Frequency domain equalization and correlative coding methods are
investigated for the ICI reduction. A first order window in time domain is
proposed and applied to correlative coding method to further enhance the BER
and Carrier to Interference Ratio (CIR) performance. A 3dB improvement is
obtained in CIR with time domain windowing method.
Peak-to-Interference Carrier Ratio (PICR) is used to measure the ICI
effect in the proposed partial transmit sequence method. It is found that
through optimization of binary phase factor value, PICR can be reduced.
Performance of the proposed methods namely EKF, time domain
windowing and partial transmit sequence methods are investigated for AWGN
channel using MATLAB simulations.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9434">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9434</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
